<div id="Idea_2825"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/2825-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_2825">open up OMB's processes&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/0-4049">jonathanhansen2001</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">9 days ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">The White House needs to explore--in a serious, explicit, and open way--how to open up the black box of OMB's influence on agency behaviors.  OMB and its many tools, which I do not enumerate here, have been used to put a gag on agencies and their employees, change the decisions of agencies, and impose presidential preferences on agencies in ways that frustrate congressional intent.  Shouldn't the public know when agents of the president are imposing their will on public servants in agencies?</div>
