<td valign="top" style="padding-right:30px; padding-left:20px;">
<div id="Idea_2802"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/2802-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_2802">Halt proliferation of classified data among agencies&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/0-4049">deep_harm</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">9 days ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">Keeping agencies open and accessible to the public is thwarted when there is a proliferation of classified data that is distributed widely among government agencies and offices even when it is not essential to their programs.  Using even one bit of classified data in an agency work product (say a classified satellite photo on which unclassified data are displayed) makes the final product unavailable to the public even though it might be important for the public to see.  proliferation of classified data also generates a need for more employees with security clearances and creates a culture of withholding information even when it is not classified. Along with clearances, agencies handling classified data have to have SCIFs, secure technology and a host of bureaucratic procedures.  When the executive branch considers sharing data, such as classified satellite data, with non-intelligence agencies, there should be a process that ensures public access is not lost for minimal information gain.</div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_2802" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_2802', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2237&topicID=2802')">Comments (1)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_2802"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2237">Making Government Operations More Open</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_2802"></div>
</div></td>
</tr>
